******
[2] Illinois
Date: Fri 27 Dec 2013
Source: WICS [edited]
http://www.wics.com/news/top-stories/stories/vid_14853.shtml


According to the Illinois Department of Public Health, 2012 was the state's largest outbreak of whooping cough since 1950. Doctors admit cases have been growing because the bacterium has spread to unvaccinated adults. It's that time of year when coughs and sniffles return, but it's what the cough sounds like that doctors say is a cause for concern. Whooping cough isn't just for kids anymore.

"Our older pertussis vaccines gave children a lot of side effects, local side effects, so they came out with a purified version. It's much safer, but the effect seems to wear off," said Dr. Steven Bowers of Memorial Health System. That means many adults are susceptible to whooping cough, even if you had a vaccine years ago. For those who keep up to date on vaccinations, you may be covered.

In 2012, Illinois reported more than 2000 whooping cough cases.

